   "source": [
    "# Global Conflict & Stability Analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "## Problem Statement\n",
    "\n",
    "- What problem are you solving?  \n",
    "As global tensions continue to rise in 2026, this project analyzes historical conflict data to understand how patterns of violence, duration of conflicts, and regional instability have evolved over time. It focuses on identifying the most affected regions, the longest-lasting conflicts, the relationship between conflict and economic performance (GDP), and periods of peak global instability.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Why does it matter?  \n",
    "The current geopolitical landscape is becoming increasingly volatile, making it essential to learn from past conflicts. By understanding where and why conflicts intensify, persist, and impact economies, we can better anticipate risks, avoid repeating historical mistakes, and develop more effective strategies for stability and peace.\n",
    "\n",
    "- What decision will this analysis support?  \n",
    "This analysis supports strategic decision-making in policy, investment, and global risk management by highlighting high-risk regions, identifying patterns behind prolonged conflicts, and revealing how instability affects economic growth—helping stakeholders take preventive and informed actions toward a more stable world."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4255af91",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dataset Overview\n",
    "---\n",
    "This notebook uses two publicly available datasets to explore the relationship between **armed conflict** and **national economic wealth**. Below is a plain-language introduction to what each dataset is, where it comes from, and what a single row actually means."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "11d8f509",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
