  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "bef2ac86",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Key Insights\n",
    "\n",
    "1. The typical country grows at approximately 3.5% annually (median), indicating a relatively stable global growth baseline over time.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. Dateset have more than 50% missing value between 1980-1990\n",
    "\n",
    "3. Two major global recessions stand out in the dataset: the 2009 Financial Crisis, where 94 countries experienced economic contraction, and the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic, where 159 countries contracted, making it the most widespread economic shock in modern history.\n",
    "\n",
    "4. Countries such as China (8.9%), Vietnam (6.3%), Bangladesh (5.2%), Cambodia (6.7%), and Bhutan (6.7%) demonstrate strong and sustained long-term economic growth, representing successful development trajectories.\n",
    "\n",
    "5. Equatorial Guinea records the highest average growth rate (~13.6%), but this is an outlier driven by a short-term oil boom rather than consistent economic development.\n",
    "\n",
    "6. Countries like South Sudan (-2.7%), Venezuela (-0.72%), Ukraine (-1.4%), and Moldova (~0%) show persistent economic underperformance, largely influenced by conflict, political instability, and weak institutional structures.\n",
    "\n",
    "7. Stable economies such as Bangladesh, Australia, Norway, and Switzerland exhibit consistent growth with low volatility, reflecting strong economic foundations and institutional stability.\n",
    "\n",
    "8. Only four countries — China, Bangladesh, Egypt, and Tanzania — have never recorded negative GDP growth in the dataset, indicating exceptional economic resilience.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
