    "#### Summary:\n",
    "\n",
    "The analysis reveals distinct patterns in how conflicts and economic instability have evolved across decades.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **THE 1990s IS THE MOST IMPORTANT DECADE IN THIS DATASET** It holds the record for minor conflicts (116), second-highest GDP crashes(56), and produced some of the worst individual country crashes (Georgia -44.9%, Rwanda -41.9%). Understanding the 1990s is central to understanding the entire conflict-GDP relationship.\n",
    "\n",
    "- In earlier decades (**1950s–1970s**), **major conflicts were more dominant**, indicating fewer but larger-scale wars compared to later periods.\n",
    "\n",
    "- In recent decades, the pattern has shifted toward **more frequent but smaller (minor) conflicts**, while **major conflicts have significantly declined**, especially in the **2010s and 2020s**.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **The 2020s already have the highest GDP crash count despite covering only 4–5 years**. COVID-19 was uniquely destructive because it hit every type of economy simultaneously — rich, poor, large, small, conflict-affected and peaceful alike. No prior crisis achieved this breadth.\n",
    "\n",
    "- **CONFLICT PEAKED IN THE 1990s, GDP CRASHES PEAKED IN THE 2020s**. These are driven by fundamentally different causes. Conflict peaked from geopolitical fragmentation; GDP crashes peaked from a global pandemic. This shows economic damage does not require conflict — a biological shock can be as economically devastating as war.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Key Insight:\n",
    "There is a clear **shift from large-scale wars to fragmented conflicts and global economic shocks**, indicating that modern instability is increasingly driven by **internal conflicts and systemic global disruptions rather than traditional warfare**."
   ]
