    "### Key Insight: Median GDP Growth is Higher During Conflict Years\n",
    "\n",
    "- The **median GDP growth during conflict years (4.15%) is higher than in stable years (3.50%)**, which is a counterintuitive finding.\n",
    "- This indicates that in a *typical case*, many economies continue to grow at a healthy rate even during periods of conflict.\n",
    "- However, the **lower mean in conflict years (3.06%) compared to stable years (3.46%)** suggests the presence of **extreme negative outliers** that drag the average down.\n",
    "- This implies that conflict does not uniformly damage all economies; instead, it creates **uneven economic impacts**, where some countries are severely affected while others remain resilient or even grow.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Interpretation\n",
    "- Conflict is **not the sole driver of GDP decline**.\n",
    "- Other macroeconomic shocks such as:\n",
    "  - global crises (e.g., pandemics)\n",
    "  - financial instability\n",
    "  - policy failures  \n",
    "  can also significantly impact GDP performance.\n",
    "- Therefore, economic downturns should be understood as **multi-factor phenomena**, not attributed to conflict alone."
