   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "# Final Report — Global Conflict & Economic Stability Analysis\n",
    "### A Data-Driven Study of Armed Conflict and GDP Growth (1946–2024)\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Project Objective\n",
    "\n",
    "This project set out to answer two core research questions using real-world geopolitical and economic data:\n",
    "\n",
    "> **Q1. Which time period saw the biggest spikes in global instability?**\n",
    ">\n",
    "> **Q2. Does conflict affect a country's wealth (GDP)?**\n",
    "\n",
    "To answer these, two globally recognised datasets were combined — the UCDP Armed Conflict database (covering 1946–2024) and the IMF/World GDP Growth Rate dataset (1980–2024) — and analysed across regions, decades, and individual countries.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Q1 Answer — When Was the World Most Unstable?\n",
    "\n",
    "**The 1990s was the most unstable decade in modern history.**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Decade | Minor Conflicts | Major Wars | GDP Crashes |\n",
    "|--------|----------------|------------|-------------|\n",
    "| 1940s  | 13             | 11         | —           |\n",
    "| 1950s  | 27             | 16 (peak)  | —           |\n",
    "| 1960s  | 41             | 14         | —           |\n",
    "| 1970s  | 37             | 18 (peak)  | —           |\n",
    "| 1980s  | 56             | 10         | —           |\n",
    "| **1990s** | **116 (peak)** | 12     | **56**      |\n",
    "| 2000s  | 61             | 12         | 37          |\n",
    "| 2010s  | 93             | 4          | 16          |\n",
    "| 2020s  | 31*            | 1*         | **87 (peak)**|\n",
    "\n",
    "*2020s count is partial — decade is not complete.\n",
    "\n",
    "The collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991 simultaneously destabilised Eastern Europe, Central Asia, and parts of Africa — creating a wave of civil wars, border disputes, and state collapses unlike anything seen in the post-WWII era. The 1990s recorded **116 minor conflicts** — more than double any other decade — alongside devastating economic crashes in Georgia (-44.9%), Rwanda (-41.9%), and Kuwait (-41%).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Two distinct patterns emerged:**\n",
    "- **Major wars declined** sharply after the 1970s (18 wars in 1970s → 1 in 2020s). The world has fewer full-scale interstate wars.\n",
    "- **Minor conflicts remained high** throughout the 2000s and 2010s. Violence did not disappear — it fragmented into chronic low-intensity insurgencies, particularly in Africa and Asia.\n",
    "\n",
    "The **2020s** hold the record for GDP crashes (87 countries) not because of conflict, but because COVID-19 in 2020 caused 159 countries to contract simultaneously — the single most economically damaging year in the dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Q2 Answer — Does Conflict Affect a Country's GDP?\n",
    "\n",
    "**Yes — but the relationship is more nuanced than a simple yes.**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Metric             | Stable Years | Conflict Years | Difference |\n",
    "|--------------------|-------------|----------------|------------|\n",
    "| Mean GDP Growth    | 3.46%       | 3.06%          | **−0.40pp**|\n",
    "| Median GDP Growth  | 3.50%       | 4.15%          | +0.65pp    |\n",
    "| Recession Rate     | ~16%        | higher         | —          |\n",
    "\n",
    "The mean drops during conflict (-0.40pp) but the median rises (+0.65pp). This apparent contradiction is explained by the composition of conflict countries — many are fast-growing Asian economies (India, Philippines, Myanmar) where conflicts run alongside strong structural growth, pushing the median up. Meanwhile, a small number of countries experience catastrophic collapses that drag the mean down.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The real damage shows at the country level:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Country       | GDP Stable Avg | GDP Conflict Avg | Penalty  |\n",
    "|---------------|---------------|-----------------|----------|\n",
    "| Moldova       | +0.94%        | −29.70%         | **−30.6pp** |\n",
    "| Georgia       | +4.95%        | −17.42%         | **−22.4pp** |\n",
    "| Libya         | +6.38%        | −10.43%         | **−16.8pp** |\n",
    "| Yemen         | +2.75%        | −8.72%          | **−11.5pp** |\n",
    "| Sierra Leone  | +5.56%        | −4.85%          | **−10.4pp** |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Full-scale war (intensity level 2) is categorically more damaging** than minor conflict. Wars produced a mean GDP of **−2.56%**, while minor conflicts averaged **+3.45%**. This 6 percentage point gap is the clearest statistical signal in the dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Four Key Insights from the Entire Project\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. The 1990s was a uniquely catastrophic decade.**  \n",
    "No other decade simultaneously held the record for minor conflicts, significant GDP crashes, and some of the worst individual country collapses. The Soviet dissolution was the single biggest driver of global instability in the post-WWII era.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. The world has fewer wars but more chronic conflicts.**  \n",
    "Major wars declined from 18 in the 1970s to just 1 in the 2020s. But minor conflicts stayed high through the 2010s. The nature of global violence has shifted — from interstate wars to intrastate insurgencies driven by non-state actors (IS, AQIM, ELN, PKK).\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. COVID-19 caused more GDP damage in one year than all conflicts combined in a decade.**  \n",
    "The 2020s GDP crash count (87) already exceeds any conflict-heavy decade. A single biological shock was more economically destructive than the post-Cold War conflict wave — highlighting that structural fragility, not just conflict, determines economic outcomes.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Conflict's economic damage is concentrated, not universal.**  \n",
    "The top 10 worst-affected countries (Moldova, Georgia, Libya, Yemen, Sierra Leone) account for a disproportionate share of the total damage. Most conflict countries continue to grow. This means conflict risk is highly country-specific and cannot be generalised globally.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Limitations\n",
    "\n",
    "- GDP data starts from 1980 (or 1990 after cleaning), leaving pre-1980 conflicts unanalysed economically.\n",
    "- GDP growth % is nominal and affected by exchange rates — some spikes are currency effects, not real economic change (e.g. Euro adoption countries in 1999).\n",
    "- Multi-country conflict episodes (e.g. Gulf War involving multiple governments) cannot be cleanly attributed to a single country.\n",
    "\n",
